"title": "5108: Paul, life of",
"media_type": "Text",
"index_reference": "5108: paul, life of",
"language": "eng",
"review_level": "None",
"content": "<p>Paul, previously known as Saul, had been a zealous persecutor of the church, but an encounter with the risen Christ (c. A.D. 35) led to his becoming the apostle to the Gentiles, with a mission to proclaim the gospel throughout the Gentile world. He was probably martyred during the persecutions of Nero, possibly in A.D. 67.</p>\n<h2>Paul's early life</h2>\n<h3>His Jewish heritage</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Phil3:4-Phil3:5\">PHP 3:4–3:5</a></strong></p>\n<h3>His citizenship</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts22:27-Acts22:28\">ACT 22:27–22:28</a></strong></p>\n<h3>His place of birth and education</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts22:3\">ACT 22:3</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts21:39\">ACT 21:39</a></p>\n<h3>His trade as a tentmaker</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts18:1-Acts18:3\">ACT 18:1–18:3</a></p>\n<h2>Paul's conversion</h2>\n<h3>His persecution of the church</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Phil3:5-Phil3:6\">PHP 3:5–3:6</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts7:59-Acts8:3\">ACT 7:59–8:3</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts9:1-Acts9:2\">ACT 9:1–9:2</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts22:19-Acts22:20\">ACT 22:19–22:20</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gal1:13\">GAL 1:13</a></p>\n<h3>His conversion on the road to Damascus and his apostolic calling</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts9:1-Acts9:19\">ACT 9:1–9:19</a> parallels <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts22:3-Acts22:16\">ACT 22:3–22:16</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts26:9-Acts26:18\">ACT 26:9–26:18</a></p>\n<h2>Paul's early Christian activity</h2>\n<h3>His journey to Arabia</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gal1:15-Gal1:17\">GAL 1:15–1:17</a></strong> <em>Acts makes no mention of this trip, but it seems that Paul went to Arabia immediately after he met Ananias and then subsequently returned to preach in Damascus.</em></p>\n<h3>His return to Damascus</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Cor11:32-2Cor11:33\">2CO 11:32–11:33</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts9:19-Acts9:25\">ACT 9:19–9:25</a></p>\n<h3>His visit to Jerusalem (c. A.D. 38)</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gal1:18\">GAL 1:18</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts9:26-Acts9:28\">ACT 9:26–9:28</a></p>\n<h3>His return to his home town of Tarsus</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts9:29-Acts9:30\">ACT 9:29–9:30</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gal1:21\">GAL 1:21</a> <em>Tarsus was in Cilicia.</em></p>\n<h3>His stay in Antioch</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts11:25-Acts11:26\">ACT 11:25–11:26</a></strong></p>\n<h2>Paul's first missionary journey and his partnership with Barnabas (c. A.D. 46–48)</h2>\n<p><em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts13:1-Acts13:6\">ACT 13:1–13:6</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts13:13-Acts13:14\">ACT 13:13–13:14</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts13:49-Acts13:51\">ACT 13:49–13:51</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts14:1\">ACT 14:1</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts14:5-Acts14:7\">ACT 14:5–14:7</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts14:21-Acts14:28\">ACT 14:21–14:28</a></p>\n<h2>Paul and the Council of Jerusalem (c. A.D. 49)</h2>\n<p>The similarities between Paul and Luke here suggests that both writers are referring to the same events in these passages. Some, however, prefer to equate the meeting recorded in <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gal2:1-Gal2:10\">Gal 2:1–10</a> with the journey to Jerusalem mentioned in <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts11:30\">Ac 11:30</a>:\n <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts15:1-Acts15:6\">ACT 15:1–15:6</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts15:22-Acts15:35\">ACT 15:22–15:35</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gal2:1-Gal2:10\">GAL 2:1–2:10</a></p>\n<h2>Paul's second missionary journey (c. A.D. 50–52)</h2>\n<h3>His disagreement with Barnabas and his new partnership with Silas</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts15:36-Acts15:41\">ACT 15:36–15:41</a></p>\n<h3>In Asia Minor</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts16:6-Acts16:8\">ACT 16:6–16:8</a></p>\n<h3>In Macedonia</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts16:9-Acts16:12\">ACT 16:9–16:12</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts17:1\">ACT 17:1</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts17:10\">ACT 17:10</a></p>\n<h3>In Greece</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts17:15\">ACT 17:15</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts18:1\">ACT 18:1</a> <em>It was from Corinth that Paul wrote to the Thessalonians.</em></p>\n<h3>His return to Antioch</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts18:18-Acts18:22\">ACT 18:18–18:22</a></p>\n<h2>Paul's third missionary journey (c. A.D. 53–57)</h2>\n<h3>His general purpose in making his journey</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts18:23\">ACT 18:23</a></strong></p>\n<h3>At Ephesus</h3>\n<p><em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts19:1-Acts19:12\">ACT 19:1–19:12</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Cor15:32\">1CO 15:32</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Cor16:8-1Cor16:9\">1CO 16:8–16:9</a></p>\n<h3>His visit to Corinth</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Cor1:15-2Cor1:16\">2CO 1:15–1:16</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Cor1:23-2Cor2:4\">2CO 1:23–2:4</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Cor13:2\">2CO 13:2</a> <em>Most scholars believe that Paul wrote 1Corinthians from Ephesus, and that he also visited Corinth during this period. This visit, however, proved to be such a painful experience for him that he abandoned plans for a third visit, and instead wrote the Corinthians a “tearful” letter, calling them to repent of their sinful behaviour.</em></p>\n<h3>His journey to Greece</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts20:1-Acts20:6\">ACT 20:1–20:6</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Cor2:12-2Cor2:13\">2CO 2:12–2:13</a> <em>Paul had hoped that Titus would bring him news from Corinth. They finally met in Macedonia, and Titus brought good news about the Corinthians' change of heart. Paul then wrote 2Corinthians before visiting Corinth for a third time.</em></p>\n<h3>His return to Jerusalem with the collection</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts20:6\">ACT 20:6</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts20:13-Acts20:16\">ACT 20:13–20:16</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts21:1-Acts21:8\">ACT 21:1–21:8</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts21:15\">ACT 21:15</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts21:17-Acts21:19\">ACT 21:17–21:19</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rom15:25-Rom15:26\">ROM 15:25–15:26</a> <em>Paul wrote Romans at this point in his travels. There is a considerable degree of uncertainty as to precisely when Galatians, Ephesians, Philippians, Colossians and Philemon were written.</em></p>\n<h2>Paul under arrest</h2>\n<h3>His life threatened in Jerusalem</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts21:27-Acts21:34\">ACT 21:27–21:34</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts23:12-Acts23:21\">ACT 23:12–23:21</a></p>\n<h3>In Caesarea (c. A.D. 57–59)</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts23:23-Acts23:35\">ACT 23:23–23:35</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts24:23-Acts24:27\">ACT 24:23–24:27</a></p>\n<h3>His appeal to Caesar</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts25:1-Acts25:12\">ACT 25:1–25:12</a></p>\n<h3>His shipwreck</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts27:1-Acts28:10\">ACT 27:1–28:10</a></p>\n<h3>His visit to Rome (c. A.D. 60)</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts28:11-Acts28:16\">ACT 28:11–28:16</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts28:30-Acts28:31\">ACT 28:30–28:31</a></p>\n<h2>The latter part of Paul's life</h2>\n<p>These verses from the Pastoral Epistles may indicate that Paul was ultimately released and undertook further journeys in the Eastern Mediterranean before his death:\n <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Tim1:3\">1TI 1:3</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Tim4:13\">2TI 4:13</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Tim4:20\">2TI 4:20</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Titus1:5\">TIT 1:5</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Titus3:12\">TIT 3:12</a></p>",
